# set up plotting theme
theme_jason <- function(legend_pos="top", base_size=12, font=NA){
  
  # come up with some default text details
  txt <- element_text(size = base_size+3, colour = "black", face = "plain")
  bold_txt <- element_text(size = base_size+3, colour = "black", face = "bold")
  
  # use the theme_minimal() theme as a baseline
  theme_minimal(base_size = base_size, base_family = font)+
    theme(text = txt,
          # axis title and text
          axis.title.x = element_text(size = 15, hjust = 1),
          axis.title.y = element_text(size = 15),
          # gridlines on plot
          panel.grid.major = element_line(linetype = 2),
          panel.grid.minor = element_line(linetype = 2),
          # title and subtitle text
          plot.title = element_text(size = 18, colour = "grey25", face = "bold"),
          plot.subtitle = element_text(size = 16, colour = "grey44"),

          ###### clean up!
          legend.key = element_blank(),
          # the strip.* arguments are for faceted plots
          strip.background = element_blank(),
          strip.text = element_text(face = "bold", size = 13, colour = "grey35")) +

    #----- AXIS -----#
    theme(
      #### remove Tick marks
      axis.ticks=element_blank(),

      ### legend depends on argument in function and no title
      legend.position = legend_pos,
      legend.title = element_blank(),
      legend.background = element_rect(fill = NULL, size = 0.5,linetype = 2)

    )
}

Key Takeaways

In this analysis my goal was to identify what factors contribute to the success of underdog teams. The key traits of cinderella teams that pulled of upsets in the past are: 1) They are strong defensively, 2) Create extra possessions by creating turnovers and by crashing the boards. 3) They tend to play a high risk high reward style of game. But there are some traits cannot be quantified in terms of offensive and defensive stats moreover, overall success in the tournament correlates with offensive rebounds and turnover and it is not limited just to underdogs. Statistics like Offensive rebounds tells us that teams that secures more rebounds wins more often than not. Whereas a more local insight can be obtained by comparing teams that had success in previous tournaments. This local insight tells us how similar a given team is to past successful teams and given the similarity, what is the probability that they can pull off an upset. The similarity approach yields some interesting results as we try to infer why some of the upsets occurred. Especially the historic 16 vs 1 upset that occurred in 2018. This approach when combined with a more global approach that uses box statistics provides us with an effective way to quantify success. The model has a good performance in terms of precision and recall based on back testing the model on the past four tournaments. The model has a precision of 62 percent, while also identifying 75 percent of upsets in the first round.

1 Introduction

Every year basketball fans around the globe hope that at least one underdog team coming out of nowhere makes a deep run in the tournament, busting millions of brackets as a result. March madness grew into a most watched sporting event not because of pedigree schools like Kansas, Duke or UNC, its because of the little know programs who make improbable runs. What makes march madness so exciting? Its probably because of the number of upsets that occur every year. However, upon closer examination, the structure of the NCAA tournament is designed for upsets as noted by Erik Johansson. Looking at the tournament data from 2003-2018, after the first two rounds of the tournament, we notice something interesting. As the tournament progresses, there are more 11 seeds remaining than 8,9 or 10 seeds.

findMatchupRound <- function(seed1, seed2){
  team1Rounds   <- unique(SeedRoundSlots$game_slot[which(SeedRoundSlots$seed == seed1)])
  team2Rounds   <- unique(SeedRoundSlots$game_slot[which(SeedRoundSlots$seed == seed2)])
  intersection  <- team1Rounds[which(team1Rounds %in% team2Rounds)]
  intersectionNum <- SeedRoundSlots$game_round[which(SeedRoundSlots$game_slot %in% intersection)]
  return(min(intersectionNum))
}

2 Modeling Approach

Now that we have the preliminaries out of the way, the coming sections would focus on predicting the upsets that happen in the first round. However,this approach can be extended to later rounds as well.

2.1 Estimation data

I used the tournament data from 2003-2019 for model development. The data was modified such that first team was the underdog. The upset was defined as any team seeded 8 or higher defeats a team that has a lower seed. Based on this definition of upset, there were 303 upsets over the span of 17 years. The offensive and defensive stats along with ordinal ranks were calculated using regular season data.

2.2 Variable Selection

A lot of effort was put into identifying key variables that correlate with upsets. Based on the current literature (Brenan and Keating), the key traits of successful Candelilla teams are 1) They are efficient offensively; 2) They take care of the ball and 3) They employ a high risk high reward strategy, they try to win extra possessions by crashing the boards, generating steals, maximizes second chance opportunity by taking a lot of three point shots. Which results in high variability in scoring.

Other ways to quantify success of underdogs is by calculating rankings based on how individual team is central are to the whole network. If each node is a division 1 team and they are connected to other teams based on the outcome of head to head games. The weight of each edge depends on the quality of the win, the edge weights were derived using sokols LRMC model. A team that beats other good teams are more central to the network than team with bad losses. A simple way of thinking about this is, each team starts with equal number of quality points, after each game some of the quality point is redistributed to the winning team from the losing team. As the season progresses, the teams with lot of wins will have more quality points thus have a high centrality.

Based on Brenan and Keating’s blog on giant killers, teams that are more chaotic, tends to pull off upsets. The idea being that if a team wins all the games that it is expected to, it would just re-enforce the existing connections. But, if a team pulls off some unexpected wins they would create new edges, thus changing the overall network orientation. Thus centrality measures provide valuable information regarding team quality.

For most of the underdog teams that make a deep run in the tournament, their eigen centrality score is in the top 50. The eigen rank when compared to kenpom ratings for underdog teams that won at least 2 games in the tournament performs well or better in some years seen from the tables below.

tourn=read.csv("MNCAATourneyCompactResults.csv")
teams = read.csv("Teams.csv")
tourney_stats_compact <- tourn %>%

# then create a feature to label the round of the tournament

  mutate(TourneyRound = ifelse(DayNum %in% c(134, 135), "Play In",(ifelse(DayNum %in% c(136, 137), "First Round", ifelse(DayNum %in% c(138, 139), "Second Round", ifelse(DayNum %in% c(143, 144), "Sweet 16", ifelse(DayNum %in% c(145, 146), "Elite 8", ifelse(DayNum == 152, "Final Four", "Championship Game")))))))) %>%
  mutate(TourneyRound = factor(TourneyRound, levels = c("First Round", "Second Round", "Sweet 16", "Elite 8", "Final Four", "Championship Game")))
EC_N = fread("Eigen_Centrality.csv")
massey_pom_end <-read_csv("MMasseyOrdinals.csv") %>%
  filter(RankingDayNum == max(RankingDayNum)) %>% ungroup() %>% # select the latest date of the season
  filter(SystemName == "POM") %>% # filter out only Pomeroy rankings
  group_by(Season, TeamID) %>%
  filter(RankingDayNum == max(RankingDayNum)) %>% ungroup() %>% # select the latest date of the season
  dplyr::select(Season, TeamID, OrdinalRank)

tourney_seeds = read_csv("NCAATourneySeeds.csv")
tourney_stats_compact %>%
  filter(Season >= 2003) %>%
  left_join(tourney_seeds, by = c("Season", "WTeamID" = "TeamID")) %>%
  left_join(tourney_seeds, by = c("Season", "LTeamID" = "TeamID")) %>%
  rename(WinnerSeed = Seed.x, LoserSeed = Seed.y) %>%
  mutate(WinnerSeed = as.numeric(substring(WinnerSeed,2,3))) %>%
  filter(WinnerSeed > 8) %>%
  left_join(EC_N, by = c("Season", "WTeamID" = "TeamID")) %>%
  filter(TourneyRound %in% c("Sweet 16","Elite 8","Final Four","Championship Game")) %>%
  distinct(Season,WTeamName,Rank_EC) %>%
  dplyr::select(Season,WTeamName, Rank_EC)  %>% head(10) %>% DT::datatable(caption = "Eigen Rank of Teams that won atleast 2 games in the tournament")

A deeper look at the comparison of kenpom rank and eigen rank reveals that the eigen rank is comparable to the kenpom rankings in terms of predicting tournament outcomes assuming that the team with higher ordinal rank wins. When comparing the round by round performance, the eigen rank outperforms the kenpom rankings.

rankings_tourney_analysis_pom <- tourney_stats_compact %>%
  filter(Season >= 2003) %>%
  left_join(massey_pom_end, by = c("Season", "WTeamID" = "TeamID")) %>%
  rename(WinnerRank = OrdinalRank) %>%
  left_join(massey_pom_end, by = c("Season", "LTeamID" = "TeamID")) %>%
  rename(LoserRank = OrdinalRank) %>%
  filter(DayNum >= 136) %>%
  # create a feature that classifies whether the winner was higher or lower ranked
  mutate(WinnerHigher_yes_no = ifelse(WinnerRank < LoserRank, "Winner Ranked Better", "Loser Ranked Better")) 


rankings_tourney_summary_pom <- rankings_tourney_analysis_pom %>%
  group_by(Season, WinnerHigher_yes_no) %>%
  summarise(n = n()) %>%
  mutate(prop = round(n / sum(n), 4))

The goal was to identify what separates the cinderella teams from the rest of the field and how can it be quantified in terms of probability to pulling of an upset. I defined upset as any team seeded 8 or above that defeats a team that is atleast 1 seed lower. The model uses average statistics from regular season games, along with some rankings such as kenpom and other derived ranking based on centrality measures.

2.3 The overall modeling approach

  1. A local similarity based approach that calculates a similarity score by comparing each team to past teams that played in the tournament
  2. A similarity based approach based on the ESPN giant killers blog where high seeded teams are compared to past underdogs that pulled off an upset and lower seeded teams that lost to underdogs
  3. A global approach based on team wise stats depending on the matchup

The similarity models uses offensive and defensive statistics as input variables and uses KNN to find the nearest 5 neighbors from teams that have won at least 1 game in the past tournaments starting from 2003. The distance of the neighbors are then aggregated and processed to calculate a composite score. The composite score gives more weight to neighbors that made a deep run in tournament and that have a better ordinal rank. The idea behind this is that a strong neighbor (one with better ordinal rank and deep tournament run in the past) should be more influential than others given that they are close to the current team that. Each year all 68 teams that make into the tournament are compared with the teams from past tournaments and five nearest neighbors are chosen based on Euclidean distance. The input variables are preprocessed by extracting the principal components.

findMatchupRound <- function(seed1, seed2){
  team1Rounds   <- unique(SeedRoundSlots$game_slot[which(SeedRoundSlots$seed == seed1)])
  team2Rounds   <- unique(SeedRoundSlots$game_slot[which(SeedRoundSlots$seed == seed2)])
  intersection  <- team1Rounds[which(team1Rounds %in% team2Rounds)]
  intersectionNum <- SeedRoundSlots$game_round[which(SeedRoundSlots$game_slot %in% intersection)]
  return(min(intersectionNum))
}

These results may explain why the Loyola Chicago team had a successful run, mainly because their profile was similar to past successful teams.

On the other hand, taking a closer look at the University of Miami (FL) team which was the first-round opponent of Loyola Chicago, its nearest neighbors are Gonzaga Bulldogs (2012), Iowa (2015), LSU (2009), Xavier (2010) and Temple (2011). None of the teams except Xavier won more than 1 game, suggesting that the Miami team was a weaker opponent based on its nearest neighbors.

Nearest Neighbor UMBC (2018).

All these results suggest that instead of using raw statistics, smilarity measures based on these statsitcs can be more effective in identifyting potential upsets for a given match-up.

The results from the second similarity based approach based on the ESPN giant killers blog follows a similar approach as the first one except that in this approach lower seeded teams are compared to past underdogs who pulled off upsets and the higher seeded teams that lost to underdogs. ESPN looks for potential upsets by looking for teams that are stronger than their seed would suggest or by finding match-ups where the weaker seeded team has a strength that could exploit the weakness of a stronger team (Brenner and Keating 2015; Dutta, 2017).

ESPN defines four subgroups of favourite teams that are susceptible to upset:

  1. Power giants: Crash the offensive board, decent defensive rebounders and do not force many turnovers
  2. Gambling giants: Crash the offensive board, weak defensive rebounding, force many turnovers
  3. Pack-line giants: Average offensive rebounding, do not force many turnovers, good defensive rebounding
  4. Generic giants: Generally skilled, not specifically strong in offensive rebounding or generating turnovers

ESPN also defines four categories of low seed teams that have the potential to upset:
1. Generic killers: Decent teams with no especially strong rebounding, turnovers, shooting, or defense 2. Slow killers: Strong offensive rebounding, limit opponent shooting, neither generate steals nor shoot 3-point shots 3. Perimeter killers: Strong 3-point shooters, generate lots of steals, weak offensive rebounding, weak at limiting opponent shooting 4. High-possession killers: Limit opponent shot accuracy, strong offensive rebounding, do not shoot many 3-point shots

These categories are then analyzed to see which Giants (high seed teams) could fall to which Giant killers (low seed teams). ESPN’s conclusions are shown in figure below, where an arrow from a Giant to a Giant killer means that the Giant is weak against that Giant killer and an arrow from a Giant killer to a Giant means that the Giant killer is strong against that Giant.

knitr::include_graphics("Giant_Killers.jpg")

The resulting subgroups for the giants and killers are shown in the table below./ Based on the graphic above, pack line giants are suseptible to upset by high possession killers. Nearest Neighbor UVA (2018).

The advantages of a similarity-based approach is that it tries to extract information in a small region without generalization. This approach tries to answer given that a higher seeded team is similar to the teams in the past that made a deep run in the NCAA tournament, how likely are they to win compared to other teams that don’t resemble cinderella teams? The similarity-based measures are them mapped to probabilities of upset by using a logistic regression.

The final model is a combination of 3 models, 2 based on similarity scores and the third is a simple logistic regression based on season long offensive and defensive statistics. The variables used for the third model belong to the following groups 1) Rebounds 2) Efficiency and 4) Possessions. Each of the variables were chosen based on the current literature as well as wells as cross-validation. The plots of some of the variables are shown in the plots below.

findMatchupRound <- function(seed1, seed2){
  team1Rounds   <- unique(SeedRoundSlots$game_slot[which(SeedRoundSlots$seed == seed1)])
  team2Rounds   <- unique(SeedRoundSlots$game_slot[which(SeedRoundSlots$seed == seed2)])
  intersection  <- team1Rounds[which(team1Rounds %in% team2Rounds)]
  intersectionNum <- SeedRoundSlots$game_round[which(SeedRoundSlots$game_slot %in% intersection)]
  return(min(intersectionNum))
}

2.4 Results and Performance

The model was trained and validated using walk-forward test. I used F1 score as a metric to assess goodness of fit. F1 statistic is an appropriate metric as it takes into account both precision and recall. Precision is the percentages of upsets correctly predicted, whereas recall measures percent of upsets that were predicted by the model. The results of back-testing the model on past four tournaments yields promising results. Overall the model has a precision of 75 percent and a recall of 63 percent on past for tournaments.

cm <- caret::confusionMatrix(data = factor(resp), reference = factor(test3$Winner))
draw_confusion_matrix <- function(cm) {

  layout(matrix(c(1,1,2)))
  par(mar=c(2,2,2,2))
  plot(c(100, 345), c(300, 450), type = "n", xlab="", ylab="", xaxt='n', yaxt='n')

  # create the matrix 
  rect(150, 430, 240, 370, col='#3F97D0')
  text(195, 435, 'No-Upset', cex=1.2)
  rect(250, 430, 340, 370, col='#F7AD50')
  text(295, 435, 'Upset', cex=1.2)
  text(125, 370, 'Predicted', cex=1.3, srt=90, font=2)
  text(245, 450, 'Actual', cex=1.3, font=2)
  rect(150, 305, 240, 365, col='#F7AD50')
  rect(250, 305, 340, 365, col='#3F97D0')
  text(140, 400, 'No-Upset', cex=1.2, srt=90)
  text(140, 335, 'Upset', cex=1.2, srt=90)

  # add in the cm results 
  res <- as.numeric(cm$table)
  text(195, 400, res[1], cex=1.6, font=2, col='white')
  text(195, 335, res[2], cex=1.6, font=2, col='white')
  text(295, 400, res[3], cex=1.6, font=2, col='white')
  text(295, 335, res[4], cex=1.6, font=2, col='white')

  # add in the specifics 
  plot(c(100, 0), c(100, 0), type = "n", xlab="", ylab="", main = "DETAILS", xaxt='n', yaxt='n')
  text(10, 85, names(cm$byClass[1]), cex=1.2, font=2)
  text(10, 70, round(as.numeric(cm$byClass[1]), 3), cex=1.2)

3 Conclusion

Based on the model results we can conclude that the similarity based approach can be used in identifying teams that are more likely to pull off an upset. The advantage of this approach is that it looks at the local trends in the data to identify similar teams. Given that it is hard to quantify underdog success using offensive or defensive stats because those stats are not unique to success of cinderella teams but to success of all teams in general.The resulting model has a good performance based on back-testing resultw.
